WaveSyncDB — Dual License
=========================

WaveSyncDB is dual-licensed. You may use, modify, and distribute it under
either of the two licenses described below — pick the one that fits your
project. You are not required to choose: the licenses run in parallel and
either is sufficient.

  1. Open Source — GNU Affero General Public License, version 3 or later (AGPL-3.0-or-later)
     SPDX:    AGPL-3.0-or-later
     Text:    LICENSE-AGPL
     Use it when:
       - Your project itself is licensed under an AGPL-compatible
         open-source license (AGPLv3, GPLv3 with the FSF's compatibility
         provision, ...).
       - You are willing to release your derivative work under the AGPL
         and publish its source code, including modifications used to
         provide a network service to remote users (AGPL section 13).
     Cost:    Free.

  2. Commercial — WaveSyncDB Commercial License
     SPDX:    LicenseRef-Commercial
     Text:    LICENSE-COMMERCIAL
     Use it when:
       - You are building closed-source, proprietary, or otherwise
         non-AGPL-compatible software (including SaaS products that
         do not publish their backend source, shipped binaries with
         restricted source, or apps distributed on commercial app
         stores under proprietary EULAs).
       - You do not wish to publish the source of your application
         under the AGPL — including modifications to a network-facing
         relay or backend.
     Cost:    Negotiated per agreement. Contact pablo13vazquez@gmail.com.

You only need to comply with one of the two. Distributing WaveSyncDB
under the AGPL does not waive your right to subsequently obtain a
commercial license, and obtaining a commercial license does not require
you to remove existing AGPL distributions.

Note on AGPL section 13: AGPL extends copyleft to network use. If you
run a modified version of WaveSyncDB or its relay server as part of a
service that lets users interact with it remotely, AGPL requires you to
offer those users the corresponding source. If that requirement does not
work for your product, you need the commercial license — even if you
never "ship" a binary in the traditional sense.

If you are unsure which license applies to your situation, please reach
out before integrating: pablo13vazquez@gmail.com.

